<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/8594> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #8594" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/7> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "p. 736" ;
	dprr:hasID 8594 .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/2885> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #2885" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Piso fr. 38 Peter; Fast. Cap., Degrassi 50f., 124, 464f.; Fast. Ant., ib. 160f.; Plin. NH 17.244; Fest. 360 L. Their wish to build a stone theater was successfully opposed by Scipio Nasica (Liv. Per. 48; Val. Max. 2.4.2; Vell. 1.15.3; App. BC 1.28, with mistaken name and date for Scipio; Oros. 4.21.4). Cassius consulted the Pontifices regarding the dedication of a statue of Concordia (Cic. Dom. 130, and 136). M. Aemilius Lepidus was chosen Princeps Senatus for the sixth time (Liv. Per. 48). On Valerius, see Münzer, Gent. Val. 52, no. 54." ;
	dprr:hasID 2885 .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/2848> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #2848" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "See the select bibliography on the decrees recorded in Josephus AJ 12 and 14 compiled by R. Marcus in Vol. 7, pp. 775-777 of the LCL translation of Josephus." ;
	dprr:hasID 2848 .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/2847> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #2847" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Didasc. Ter. Eun. and Phorm.; Fast. Cap., Degrassi 50f., 123, 462f.; Fast. Ant., ib. 160f.; Gell. 2.24.2; 15.11.1; Chr. 354; Fast. Hyd. and Chr. Pasc., with Carbo for Strabo; Cassiod. Fannius carried the Lex Fannia, one of the earliest laws to regulate private and public banquets and distributions at games (Lucil. 1172 M; Plin. NH 10.139; Gell. 2.24.1-6; Athen. 6.108, 274c; Macrob. Sat. 3.13.13, 16.4, and 17.3-5). He may be identified with the Consul Fannius who wrote Cos requesting safe passage for returning Jewish ambassadors (Joseph. AJ 14.10.15; cf. Holleaux, {Gr}. 5; Münzer, Hermes 55 [1920] 437, note 1)." ;
	dprr:hasID 2847 .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/2823> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #2823" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "The latest possible dates for their praetorships under the Lex Villia. On Valerius, see Münzer, Gent. Val. 52, no. 54." ;
	dprr:hasID 2823 .
